* building a measure space from elementary sets
	* elementary subsets
		* generally
			* these are very simple subsets of the space which you surely know the volume of
			* now you have a mapping from elementary sets to real numbers, i will say this is your "elementary measure"
			* include the empty set among the elementary sets and map 0 to it as its volume
		* in the euclidean space
			* interval
				* 1 dimensional
					* "half closed" or "half open" interval is one which is closed at the low end and open at the high end [[a, b)]
				* multi-dimensional half closed interval is one being half-closed in all the dimensions
				* a "brick" is a half-closed any-dimensional interval
			* a "brick function" function is one for which a brick exists in its domain such that the function maps the points of the brick to (real value h) and the other points of the domain to 0
			* if h = 1 then the function is a "brick indicator"
			* that brick is said to be the "support" of the function
			* for intervals the measure is intuitively trivial - just the volume of the interval [the product of its sizes in each dimension]
